04737nam a22007455i 9789814881791DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20202020si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898148817917 a10.1355/97898148817912doi  a(DE-B1597)567766  a(OCoLC)1198931782  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0080002bisacsh1 aThant, Su Mon , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParty Mergers in Myanmar :bA New Development /cSu Mon Thant. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (52 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tAN UNATTRACTIVE STRATEGY BECOMES A TREND -- tCROSS-ALLIANCE COLLABORATIONS -- tA MOVE TOWARDS A SHARED FEDERAL VISION -- tCASE STUDIES: FIVE ETHNIC PARTY MERGERS -- tCONCLUSION0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aParty mergers are a new development in Myanmar politics. Given that such mergers often assist the consolidation of new democratic regimes, some broader system-wide effects may also occur. Myanmar’s ethnic parties consistently choose merger strategies over other forms of pre-electoral coalition. This highlights a transition from a focus on questions of authoritarianism and democracy to one on the creation of a federal system of government with a stronger cleavage between competing Bamar and ethnic nationalisms. Despite cooperation among political parties outside the electoral process, pre-electoral coalitions such as constituency-sharing or campaigning for allies have generally not been successful. Five of the six mergers among ethnic parties attempted prior to the 2015 general election failed. However, between 2017 and 2019, five mergers involving parties representing the Chin, Kachin, Kayah, Kayin or Karen, and Mon ethnicities, achieved success. The successful mergers were motivated not only by desires for electoral success in 2020 but also by shared federal aims, which involve ethnic parties in Chin, Kachin, Kayah, Kayin or Karen, and Mon states forming a strong local party in their respective regions to strive for ethnic equality and self-determination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aPolitical Process/ Campaign & Elections. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068959408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981488179140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814881791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814881791.jpg  a978-3-11-068959-4  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-069629-5  DG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2b2020  a978-3-11-069630-1  PP ROW Ebook Package English 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-PL